      <div xml:id="NA340-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu parattaiyiṉ maṟuttanta talaimakaṉait talaimakaḷ nontuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE said, in pain about HIM who had been brought back from the other woman.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA340">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            pullēṉ makiḻna pulattalu milaṉē</l>
<l>            kallā yāṉaik kaṭuntērc ceḻiyaṉ</l>
<l>            paṭaimāṇ peruṅkuḷa maṭainīr viṭṭeṉak</l>
<l>            kālaṇain tetiriya kaṇaikkōṭṭu vāḷai</l>
<l>            yaḷḷalaṅ kaḻaṉi yuḷvā yōṭip</l>
<l>            pakaṭucē ṟutaitta puḷḷiveṇ puṟattuc</l>
<l>            ceñcā luḻavar kōṟpuṭai matarip</l>
<l>            paiṅkāṟ ceṟuvi ṉaṉaimutaṟ puraḷum</l>
<l>            vāṇaṉ ciṟukuṭi yaṉṉaveṉ</l>
<l>            kōṉē relvaḷai ñekiḻtta nummē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>I won’t embrace [you], delightful man, and I’m not at all vexed</l>
<l>	with you who made loose my fine light bangles in a row(?),</l>
<l>	like Vāṇaṉ’s Ciṟukuṭi,</l>
<l>	where the wet base of the field with fresh [water-]channels(?) is deranged,</l>
<l>	flourishing when struck by the stick of the ploughmen in the red furrows,</l>
<l>	[their] white backs full of dots kicked [up] from the mud by the bulls,</l>
<l>	the round-finned Vāḷai fish faced with [and] touched by [their] legs</l>
<l>	running into the inner parts(?) of the muddy field,</l>
<l>	since drinking water was let out from the excellently constructed big pond</l>
<l>	of Ceḻiyaṉ with quick chariot [and] untaught elephants(?).<note place="foot">So this is once more one of the really nasty ones: partly unmarked, partly incomprehensible marking, rare words, no clearly familiar images or topoi - T.V.G.’s reading was beyond me, so I just tried to make sense as best I could.</note></l>
      </lg>
      </div>
